---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Aside from '../../../components/Aside.astro';
import {datetimeSidebar} from '../../../data/datetime-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Ranges & Time Slots" sidebar={datetimeSidebar}
            description="Date ranges, instant ranges, zoned datetime ranges, and time slots with set operations">

    <h1>Ranges &amp; Time Slots</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Time intervals at every level — from calendar date ranges to intra-day time slots —
        with containment checks, intersection tests, and set operations.
    </p>

    <h2>MpLocalDateRange</h2>

    <p>An open-ended date range <code>[from, to)</code> — the end date is <em>excluded</em>. This is the natural model
        for hotel stays, billing periods, and date iteration:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpLocalDateRange
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpLocalDate

val range = MpLocalDateRange(
    from = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 3, 10),
    to = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 3, 15),
)

println(range.numberOfDays)    // 5
println(range.numberOfNights)  // 5

// Iterate over all dates in the range
val dates = range.asListOfDates()
// [2025-03-10, 2025-03-11, 2025-03-12, 2025-03-13, 2025-03-14]

// As a period
val period = range.asDatePeriod  // MpDatePeriod(0y, 0m, 5d)

// Convert to closed
val closed = range.asClosedRange  // [2025-03-10, 2025-03-14]

// Boundaries
val forever = MpLocalDateRange.forever  // Genesis to Doomsday`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <Aside>Open-ended ranges are the right default for most business logic. A 3-night hotel stay from March 10 to March
        13 has <code>from=10, to=13</code> — you check out on the 13th, not stay through it.
    </Aside>

    <h3>MpLocalDateRange.Partial</h3>

    <p>All range types have a <strong>Partial</strong> variant for when only one boundary is known.
        This is common in search filters, open-ended subscriptions, and "from now on" queries.
        Convert to a concrete range via <code>asValidRange()</code>.</p>

    <p>When only one boundary is known — "from March 1 onwards" or "up until June":</p>

    <Code code={`// Only a start — open-ended into the future
val fromMarch = MpLocalDateRange.Partial(
    from = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 3, 1),
    to = null,
)

// Only an end — open-ended into the past
val untilJune = MpLocalDateRange.Partial(
    from = null,
    to = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 6, 1),
)

// Both null — represents "any time"
val anytime = MpLocalDateRange.Partial(from = null, to = null)

// Convert to a concrete range (fills in Genesis/Doomsday)
val concrete = fromMarch.asValidRange()
// MpLocalDateRange(2025-03-01, +10000-01-01)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>MpClosedLocalDateRange</h2>

    <p>A closed date range <code>[from, to]</code> — the end date is <em>included</em>:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpClosedLocalDateRange

val closed = MpClosedLocalDateRange(
    from = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 3, 10),
    to = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 3, 14),
)

println(closed.numberOfDays)  // 5 (includes both endpoints)

// Convert between range types
val open = closed.asOpenRange    // MpLocalDateRange [10, 15)
val back = open.asClosedRange    // MpClosedLocalDateRange [10, 14]`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>MpClosedLocalDateRange.Partial</h3>

    <Code code={`val partial = MpClosedLocalDateRange.Partial(
    from = MpLocalDate.of(2025, 3, 10),
    to = null,
)

val concrete = partial.asValidRange()
// MpClosedLocalDateRange(2025-03-10, +10000-01-01)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>MpInstantRange</h2>

    <p>A range of absolute timestamps. Supports containment checks, intersection tests, and set subtraction:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpInstantRange
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpInstant

val start = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T08:00:00Z")
val end = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T17:00:00Z")

val workday = MpInstantRange(from = start, to = end)

// Containment — is a specific instant inside this range?
val noon = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T12:00:00Z")
println(workday.contains(noon))   // true

val midnight = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T00:00:00Z")
println(workday.contains(midnight))  // false

// Intersection — do two ranges overlap?
val afternoon = MpInstantRange(
    from = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T13:00:00Z"),
    to = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T20:00:00Z"),
)
println(workday.intersects(afternoon))  // true

val nextDay = MpInstantRange(
    from = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-16T08:00:00Z"),
    to = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-16T17:00:00Z"),
)
println(workday.intersects(nextDay))  // false

// Cut — subtract one range from another
val remaining = workday.cutAway(afternoon)
// result covers 08:00–13:00 only

// Boundaries
val forever = MpInstantRange.forever  // Genesis to Doomsday`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>MpInstantRange.Partial</h3>

    <Code code={`val partial = MpInstantRange.Partial(
    from = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T08:00:00Z"),
    to = null,  // open-ended
)

val concrete = partial.asValidRange()
// MpInstantRange(2025-03-15T08:00:00Z, +10000-01-01T00:00:00Z)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>MpZonedDateTimeRange</h2>

    <p>A timezone-aware datetime range. Knows its duration and whether it has open boundaries:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpZonedDateTimeRange
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpTimezone

val berlin = MpTimezone.of("Europe/Berlin")

val range = MpZonedDateTimeRange(
    from = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T08:00:00Z").atZone(berlin),
    to = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T17:00:00Z").atZone(berlin),
)

println(range.isValid)    // true — from is before to
println(range.hasStart)   // true
println(range.hasEnd)     // true
println(range.isOpen)     // false — both boundaries present
println(range.duration)   // 9 hours`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>MpZonedDateTimeRange.Partial</h3>

    <Code code={`val partial = MpZonedDateTimeRange.Partial(
    from = MpInstant.parse("2025-03-15T08:00:00Z").atZone(berlin),
    to = null,  // open-ended
)

val concrete = partial.asValidRange()
// fills in Doomsday as the end`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>MpLocalTimeSlot</h2>

    <p>A time range within a single day. Supports merging, gap detection, splitting, and set subtraction — purpose-built
        for scheduling and availability calendars:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpLocalTimeSlot
import io.peekandpoke.ultra.datetime.MpLocalTime
import kotlin.time.Duration.Companion.minutes

val morning = MpLocalTimeSlot(
    from = MpLocalTime.of(9, 0),
    to = MpLocalTime.of(12, 0),
)

val afternoon = MpLocalTimeSlot(
    from = MpLocalTime.of(13, 0),
    to = MpLocalTime.of(17, 0),
)

// Do they touch or overlap?
println(morning.touches(afternoon))  // false (gap from 12:00 to 13:00)

// Merge adjacent/overlapping slots
val extended = MpLocalTimeSlot(
    from = MpLocalTime.of(11, 0),
    to = MpLocalTime.of(14, 0),
)
val merged = morning.mergeWith(extended)
// MpLocalTimeSlot(09:00, 14:00)

// Cut — remove one slot from another
val remaining = afternoon.cutAway(extended)
// MpLocalTimeSlot(14:00, 17:00)

// Split a slot into chunks with gaps
val chunks = morning.splitWithGaps(
    duration = 30.minutes,  // 30-minute slots
    gap = 10.minutes,       // 10-minute gaps
)
// [09:00-09:30, 09:40-10:10, 10:20-10:50]

// Containment — is a specific time inside this slot?
println(morning.contains(MpLocalTime.of(10, 30)))  // true
println(morning.contains(MpLocalTime.of(13, 0)))   // false

// Intersection — do two slots overlap?
println(morning.intersects(afternoon))  // false (gap between them)

// Adjacency — do they border without overlapping?
val lunchEnd = MpLocalTimeSlot(
    from = MpLocalTime.of(12, 0),
    to = MpLocalTime.of(13, 0),
)
println(morning.isAdjacentTo(lunchEnd))  // true

// Formatting
println(morning.formatHhMm())    // "09:00 - 12:00"
println(morning.formatHhMmSs())  // "09:00:00 - 12:00:00"`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h3>MpLocalTimeSlot.Partial</h3>

    <Code code={`val partial = MpLocalTimeSlot.Partial(
    from = MpLocalTime.of(9, 0),
    to = null,  // open-ended
)

val concrete = partial.asValidRange()
// null — both boundaries are needed for a valid time slot`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Set operations summary</h2>

    <p>Every range type supports containment checks, intersection tests, set subtraction, adjacency detection, and
        merging.
        These operations follow consistent semantics across all types:</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-8">
        <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
            <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold">Operation</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">DateRange</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">InstantRange</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">ZonedRange</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">TimeSlot</th>
            </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-gray-400">
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>contains(point)</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>contains(range)</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>intersects()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>touches()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>isAdjacentTo()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>mergeWith()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>cutAway()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="py-2"><code>Partial</code> variant</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h2>Type-specific operations</h2>

    <p>Some operations are only available on certain range types, either because they require type-specific
        information (like a timezone) or because they only make sense in a particular domain:</p>

    <div class="not-prose my-8">
        <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
            <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/10">
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold">Operation</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">DateRange</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">InstantRange</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">ZonedRange</th>
                <th class="py-2 text-white font-semibold text-center">TimeSlot</th>
            </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-gray-400">
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>duration</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>plus()</code> / <code>minus()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>asListOfDates()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>numberOfDays</code> / <code>numberOfNights</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-white/5">
                <td class="py-2"><code>asDatePeriod</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="py-2"><code>splitWithGaps()</code></td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center">-</td>
                <td class="py-2 text-center text-green-400">yes</td>
            </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <Aside>Date ranges don't expose <code>duration</code> because a day is not always 24 hours (DST transitions).
        Use <code>numberOfDays</code> or <code>asDatePeriod</code> instead.
        Similarly, <code>plus()</code>/<code>minus()</code> are not on date ranges because shifting by
        a duration would require timezone context &mdash; use the individual date's arithmetic methods instead.
    </Aside>

